# Move Zeroes
## Approach (Two Pointer Technique)
I used the two-pointer technique. One pointer (i) traverses the array, while another pointer (j)
tracks where the next non-zero element should be placed. Whenever I encounter a non-zero element,
I swap it with the element at j and increment j.
This keeps all non-zero elements in their original order while pushing zeros to the end.
The solution runs in O(n) time with O(1) extra space."

#Algorithm
1.Initialize j = 0.
2.Traverse the array using i.
3.Whenever a non-zero element is found:
  Swap nums[i] with nums[j].
  Increment j.
4.After completing the traversal, all non-zero elements are at the beginning, and all zeros automatically move to the end.

##  Java Solution
class Solution {
    public void moveZeroes(int[] nums) {
        int j = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++)  {
            if(nums[i] != 0) {
                int temp = nums[i];
                nums[i] = nums[j];
                nums[j] = temp;
                j++;
            }
        }
        
    }
}

## Time Complexity: O(n)

## Space Complexity: O(1)

